# O01 — Wire JsonlLogger as EventConsumer on WorkflowEngine

## Write Scope

`crates/roko-cli/src/run.rs` — modify `run_with_workflow_engine` only.

Do NOT touch any other file. Do NOT modify `Cargo.toml`, `lib.rs`, or any
`roko-runtime` source file.

## Dependencies

- `roko_runtime::jsonl_logger::JsonlLogger` — already exported from `roko-runtime`
- `roko_runtime::jsonl_logger::EventConsumer` — trait that `JsonlLogger` implements
- `roko_runtime::workflow_engine::WorkflowEngine` — has `add_consumer(&mut self, Arc<dyn WorkflowEventConsumer>)`
- `roko_runtime::workflow_engine::WorkflowEventConsumer` — the consumer trait on the engine

Note: There are TWO separate consumer traits in play:

1. `roko_runtime::jsonl_logger::EventConsumer` — used by `JsonlLogger` for `RuntimeEvent`s
   emitted by the EffectDriver via the global event bus
2. `roko_runtime::workflow_engine::WorkflowEventConsumer` — used by `WorkflowEngine` for
   lifecycle events (WorkflowStarted, PhaseTransition, WorkflowCompleted)

`JsonlLogger` implements `EventConsumer` for `RuntimeEvent`. It does NOT directly
implement `WorkflowEventConsumer`. You need a thin adapter struct.

## DO NOT

- Do not add new crate dependencies to any `Cargo.toml`
- Do not modify `roko-runtime` source files
- Do not change `run_once` or any other function in `run.rs`
- Do not add `#[cfg(...)]` guards — this is always-on observability
- Do not restructure the `WorkflowEngine::new(services)` call pattern

## Existing Code Context

### `crates/roko-cli/src/run.rs` — the function to modify (lines 262–328)

```rust
/// Execute a prompt via the new WorkflowEngine (event-driven architecture).
pub async fn run_with_workflow_engine(
    prompt: &str,
    workdir: &std::path::Path,
    workflow_template: &str,
    enabled_gates: Vec<String>,
) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    use roko_agent::model_call_service::ModelCallService;
    use roko_compose::prompt_assembly_service::PromptAssemblyService;
    use roko_gate::gate_service::GateService;
    use roko_learn::feedback_service::FeedbackService;

    let feedback_sink: Arc<dyn CoreFeedbackSink> =
        Arc::new(FeedbackService::from_roko_dir(&workdir.join(".roko")));
    let model_caller: Arc<dyn CoreModelCaller> = Arc::new(
        ModelCallService::new("claude-sonnet-4-20250514".to_string())
            .with_feedback_sink(Arc::clone(&feedback_sink)),
    );
    let prompt_assembler: Arc<dyn CorePromptAssembler> = Arc::new(PromptAssemblyService::new());
    let gate_runner: Arc<dyn CoreGateRunner> = Arc::new(GateService::new());

    let services = EffectServices {
        model_caller: Arc::new(RuntimeModelCallerAdapter::new(model_caller)),
        prompt_assembler: Arc::new(RuntimePromptAssemblerAdapter::new(prompt_assembler)),
        feedback_sink: Arc::new(RuntimeFeedbackSinkAdapter::new(feedback_sink)),
        gate_runner: Arc::new(RuntimeGateRunnerAdapter::new(gate_runner)),
    };

    let workflow = match workflow_template {
        "express" => WorkflowConfig::express(),
        "full" => WorkflowConfig::full(),
        _ => WorkflowConfig::standard(),
    };

    let config = WorkflowRunConfig {
        prompt: prompt.to_string(),
        workdir: workdir.to_path_buf(),
        workflow,
        enabled_gates,
        commit_prefix: Some("feat".to_string()),
    };

    // Run the workflow.
    let engine = WorkflowEngine::new(services);   // <-- add consumers HERE
    let result = engine
        .run(config)
        .await
        .map_err(|error| anyhow!("workflow engine failed: {error}"))?;

    println!(
        "Workflow complete: {} ({:?})",
        result.run_id, result.outcome
    );
    println!("Iterations: {}", result.iterations);

    Ok(())
}
```

